<br>
Neon Genesis Evangelion<br>
<br>
Okay, I'm biased here, because this is my favorite anime.  Ever.  Anywho, I'll present you with the basic story, up to the point where I shouldn't say any more.<br>
<br>
Okay, it starts out with lil' Shinji Ikari, a 15-year old Japanese boy who was born about 9 months after a disaster called the Second Impact blew up Antartica and killed off half the world's population.  Seems ol' Shinji has been called to the new city of Tokyo-3 by his bastard of a father, who abandoned him to an uncle, or a boarding school, or something just a few days after his mother's death.  Close family, huh?<br>
<br>
Shinji's met at the train station by Misato Katsuragi, a dis-proportionately built anime babe who is a Captain in a mysterious organization called NERV.  It's a good thing she shows up, because a giant monster chooses that moment to start rampaging through the city.  The UN promptly bombs the hell out of it using a N^2 (non-nuclear) warhead, apparently a bigger version of our friendly nuke, but without the fallout.  The monster decides to stand still for a few hours and regenerate, which I think is a perfectly reasonable reaction.<br>
<br>
Shinji gets hauled down to NERV's underground base (built inside a giant cavern called the GeoFront) and finds out that the Supreme Commander of NERV is his bastard father!  Seems NERV's purpose is to build giant robots to fight and destroy giant monsters called Angels.  Yep, just like the one sitting up in the city above, stewing over being nooked.<br>
<br>
Shinji's pop, Gendo Ikari, has indentified Shinji as one of the rare individuals capable of piloting these giant robots, which NERV has named Evangelions.  Good ol' Gendo wants his son to hop into Evangelion Unit One, with no training, and fight the big multistory beastie to the death.  Being what some would call shy and sensative, or what others would call a wimp, Shinji tells his father that he's not getting into no giant robot to fight no giant monster.  He also expresses his belief that this is the shittiest family reunion ever.<br>
<br>
Commander Ikari, nonplussed, calls out the first pilot, Rei Ayanami, to fight instead.  When they wheel her out on a gurney, Shinji discovers that she was seriously injured while test piloting Evangelion Unit 0.  When it becomes obvious that Rei would never survive, Shinji takes a deep breath, grows a little bit of a spine, and decides to pilot.  From there, the grand journey begins.<br>
<br>
This is all just the first half of the first episode.  Things get hairier from there.  Seems these Angels keep coming, and we learn that if they penetrate the deepest holding areas of the GeoFront, they'll do something to destroy all of humanity.  On top of all this, Shinji has to live life in his new environment, deal with the people around him.  (This includes the second pilot, who comes in later.  Shinji was actually the third pilot chosen, and the second is as exuberant and obnoxious as Shinji is quiet and depressed.)<br>
<br>
The first half of the series is the Cool Giant Robot Show, where we're treated to all the typical robot show elements, though with incredable character development thrown in.  The second half I call the Downward Spiral, where we learn of some of the plots and secrets, and the characters learn that Saving the World isn't nearly as easy or fun as it is in all those giant robot anime.  Then, there's the Series Ending, which will blow your mind.  Follow this with the movies, which show you that all the characters had their minds blown during the ending, too.<br>
<br>
In conclusion, Evangelion is the best Anime out there, or at least the best we can get here in America.  Probably the best out there, though.  If you're an anime fan, you've seen it.  If you're not an anime fan, you'd probably still enjoy it.  Just be warned, though, you can really get into Neon Genesis Evangelion, and there are some parts that can hurt you once you do.  The reward's worth it though, in my opinion.<br>
<br>
Rating:  off the damn scale<br>
<br>
